#
# WHAT IT IS
#   triage-bot is "an OpenAI-powered triage bot for a Slack support
#   channel designed to tag oncalls, prioritize issues, suggest
#   solutions, and streamline communication" — Aaron Roney's
#   slack-morphism + async-openai service.  The daemon connects to a
#   configured Slack workspace via the slack-morphism socket-mode or
#   events-API client, listens for messages posted to the configured
#   support channels, classifies each one with an OpenAI / OpenAI-
#   compatible LLM (via `async-openai`), and replies in-thread with
#   the recommended oncall mention, priority, and any suggested fix
#   context drawn from a SurrealDB-backed knowledge store.  Telemetry
#   flows to an OpenTelemetry collector via OTLP/HTTP for
#   tracing-subscriber + tracing-opentelemetry integration.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from src/bin.rs clap-derive Args struct)
#   triage-bot [-c <FILE>] [-v...]
#
#   Options:
#     -c, --config <FILE>     Override the config file path  (optional).
#                             Default search path:  `.hidden/config.toml`
#                             in the current working directory.  All
#                             remaining configuration can come from
#                             `config.toml` or environment variables.
#     -v                      Increase log verbosity  (repeatable count,
#                             via `clap::ArgAction::Count`):
#                               no flag → INFO
#                               -v       → DEBUG
#                               -vv+     → TRACE
#
#   Standard clap auto-flags:
#     -h, --help              Show help
#     -V, --version           Show version
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   Direct dependency on `slack-morphism = { version = "2",
#   features = ["hyper", "axum"] }` declared in Cargo.toml — the
#   canonical Rust Slack client maintained by Abdulla Abdurakhmanov
#   (abdolence / slack-morphism-rust).  slack-morphism provides typed
#   Rust bindings for Slack's Web API + Socket-Mode + events
#   subscription + interactive blocks, with `hyper`-backed transport
#   and an `axum`-router integration for inbound webhook handlers.
#   Verified via:
#     gh api repos/twitchax/triage-bot/contents/Cargo.toml
#       → slack-morphism = { version = "2", features = ["hyper", "axum"] }
#     gh api repos/twitchax/triage-bot/contents/src/bin.rs
#       → triage_bot::start(config).await
#   This entry is the Rust=123 leader bump that OPENS Axis 68
#   (Slack SDK Library), pairing with future Go=slack-go/slack and
#   TS-Node=@slack/web-api poles to close the axis at 1/1/1.
#
#   No completion for `triage-bot` ships with Apple zsh
#   (/usr/share/zsh/*/functions) or Homebrew zsh-completions
#   (/opt/homebrew/share/zsh/site-functions) — confirmed absent.  The
#   adjacent `more_src/_slack-cli`, `more_src/_slack-mcp-server`,
#   `more_src/_slackcat`, and `src/_slack-term` in this corpus target
#   unrelated Slack tools;  `triage-bot` is a distinct binary.
# ============================================================================

_triage-bot() {
    _arguments -s \
        '(-c --config)'{-c+,--config=}'[override config file path (default .hidden/config.toml)]:config file:_files -g "*.toml"' \
        '*-v[increase log verbosity (-v DEBUG, -vv TRACE)]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]'
}

_triage-bot "$@"
